ationhood has emerged and been maintained in the face of aggressive efforts to assimilate Native peoples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians of North America -- Civil rights. 0aIndians of North America -- Government relations. 0aIndians of North America -- Politics and government. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCivil rights. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relatins. 0aIndians of North AmericaxPolitics and government. 0aNation-building -- United States. 0aNation-buildingzUnited States. 0aNationalism -- United States. 0aNationalismzUnited States. 0aSelf-determination, National -- United States. 0aSelf-determination, NationalzUnited States. 0aUnited States -- Politics and government. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aHistory : American History. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBraun, Sebastian F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Adriana Greci, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Christina Gish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHosmer, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHosmer, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNesper, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNesper, Larry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNorrgard, Chantal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Gerald F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Joshua L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStark, Heidi Kiiwetinepinesiik, eco